== History == The exact founding date is unknown. One theory states that it was established in the 6th year of Emperor Bidatsu (577 CE) when the [[Nihamabe|Hihamabe]] clan was stationed in Hida Province, and their {{ill|Tomo no Miyatsuko|ja|伴造|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomo no Miyatsuko|qq=}} enshrined Takamimusubi no Mikoto.
During the [[Kenmu Restoration]], [[Anekōji Ietsuna]] was a11ointed governor of Hida Province in 1334 and showed great reverence for Takata Shrine. He established a residence adjacent to the shrine, which became the political center of Hida. However, after the fall of the [[Anekōji clan]] to [[Kanamori Nagachika]], the shrine's prominence declined.
In the [[Edo period]], the shrine was renamed "Hakusan Shrine" or "Hakusan Gongen Shrine." During the {{ill|Bunka era|ja|文化 (元号)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunka era|qq=}} (1804–1818), the {{ill|Urabe clan|ja|吉田家|lt=Yoshida clan|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Urabe clan|qq=}} identified it as the Takata Shrine listed in the Engishiki, and it was renamed accordingly. The formal designation of Takata Shrine as a Shikinaisha was granted in 1870 (Meiji 3).
In 1907 (Meiji 40), the shrine incorporated Suwa Shrine, Tado Shrine, and Kamo Shrine.
== Deities == * Main deity ** [[Takamimusubi|Takamimusubi no Mikoto]] * Enshrined Deities ** [[Kukurihime no Kami|Hakusan-hime no Kami]] ** [[Takeminakata|Takeminakata no Mikoto]] ** [[Kamo Wakeikazuchi|Kamo Wakeikazuchi no Mikoto]] ** [[Amatsuhikone|Amatsuhikone no Mikoto]]
== festival == The festival highlights include the Kagura Lion Dance, [[matchlock]] gun firings, and a portable shrine procession.
* Kagura Lion Dance ** A two-person [[shishi-mai]] performed by male and female pairs, featuring six different routines. It is designated as an Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property of [[Gifu Prefecture]].<ref name="kagurajishi">{{Cite web|language=ja|date= |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/mumin/hidasi/takadajinnjya.html |title=Kagura Lion Dance of Takata Shrine |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2013-04-22}}</ref> The dance is performed several times during the festival. * Matchlock Gun Firings ** Conducted at key points of the festival to purify the sacred grounds. The matchlocks are said to have been donated during the [[Sengoku period]] by {{ill|Anekōji Tokimitsu|ja|姉小路時光|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Anekōji Tokimitsu|qq=}}. * Portable Shrine Procession ** A procession including [[sakaki]], {{ill|Tengu|ja|天狗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tengu|qq=}}, armored warriors, chicken fights, male and female lions, drums, flutes, {{ill|Miko|ja|巫女|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miko|qq=}}, and the mikoshi, comprising several hundred participants.
== Cultural Properties == ;Important Intangible Folk Cultural Properties of Gifu Prefecture * Kagura Lion Dance of Takata Shrine<ref name="kagurajishi" /> ;Designated Tangible Cultural Properties of Hida City * Kabuto (helmet) of Takata Shrine<ref name="furukawacho_bunkazai">{{Cite web|language=ja|date= |url=http://www.pamph-navi.jp/art/view_dynamic/pdfView.php?src=pam10008025 |title=Furukawa Town Cultural Property Guide |format=PDF |publisher=Hida City |accessdate=2013-04-22}}</ref> * Statues of Takata Shrine Guardians<ref name="furukawacho_bunkazai" /> ;Designated Natural Monuments of Hida City * Five Great Cedars of Takata Shrine<ref name="furukawacho_bunkazai" />
== Access == * A11roximately 2 km from [[Takayama Main Line]] {{ill|Sugisaki Station|ja|杉崎駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sugisaki Station|qq=}}.
